# üß† **Strategy**  {#üß†-strategy}

*Suggested time: 1.5 \- 2 hours*

It is OK to mostly take this from our and others‚Äô [EA](https://www.notion.so/centreforeffectivealtruism/Outreach-Handbook-Full-of-Templates-f1e6013d195b47a7b5d7930743bc9ff3) [group](https://library.globalchallengesproject.org/) [organizing](https://resources.eagroups.org/) [resources](https://resources.eagroups.org/things-we-recommend-you-sign-up-to); you don‚Äôt need to reinvent the wheel\!

## **1b. Deciding on Activities**

| Given what you decided in previous sections about your goals, decide what programming you want. Try to prioritize recurring programs happening at the same time and place, over one-off events. Ensure that your programming addresses the intermediate goals and levers for your ultimate goal identified in the previous section. For example, if you‚Äôre seeking to ‚Äòincrease the number of people who dedicate their career to the world‚Äôs most pressing problems‚Äô, a career group for engaged group members will likely be more effective than a talk on water quality in Ghana. This is especially the case towards the end of term, where you should shift from broad outreach to focusing in on the most engaged people. Top tips: If you‚Äôve already drawn up semester plans, copy these in\! If you‚Äôre a pre-existing group, we recommend DMing some of your key members and asking them for feedback on your plans, and what they‚Äôd be most interested in |

## **1c. Setting Goals** {#1c.-setting-goals}

| Now you know what programming you want to run, let‚Äôs set some goals for what you‚Äôll achieve\! Types of goal to consider: Objective goals (e.g. completion and attendance numbers) X people completed our introductory program, and demonstrated active interest in continuing with the group X showed up to our introductory event or applied to our programs Subjective goals *(These can be more personal \- they don‚Äôt have to be about your planned activities\!)* I can talk candidly to X exec/board members about difficult ideas  I feel confident I can explain the core EA ideas in a way I would find accurate and compelling *Measure the right things*: It can be easy to conflate a certain ‚Äòmental image‚Äô of a "thriving EA group" with actual impact. What aspects of that mental image do you think actually contribute to your theory of change, and which parts are a distraction? For example, lots of people ‚Äòoccasionally involved‚Äô or ‚Äòsigned up‚Äô with the group seems good. But it is almost certainly better to have [a smaller number of people who are dedicated](https://www.notion.so/centreforeffectivealtruism/OSP-Guide-Spring-2025-13e3ad82014080ecbafdc16b558c74ba?pvs=4#1503ad820140801486e2e8e1b06d2e1d) to helping tackle the world‚Äôs most pressing problems. You may want to measure success using questions like ‚ÄúHow many members are likely to actually work in a neglected, high-impact area?‚Äù or ‚ÄúHave they spent time learning new skills or applying to opportunities?‚Äù If applicable, we recommend looking at outcomes from the previous semester / year as a ‚Äòbaseline‚Äô when designing your goals. E.g. If your group had 20 intro fellow applications last semester, you could aim for 22 this semester. Top Tips: Keep your theory of change in mind when setting goals \- as a group you want people actually focusing their careers on having impact\! Have a check-in meeting with co-organisers midway through the semester to see how you‚Äôre doing so far. Return to these goals at the end of your semester and see how many you‚Äôve accomplished. |
